cabal: add upper bounds

The release upload complained:

Warnings:
- These packages miss upper bounds:
- - HUnit
- - attoparsec
- - bytestring
- - containers
- - directory
- - either
- - filemanip
- - filepath
- - language-python
- - mtl
- - optparse-applicative
- - semigroups
- - split
- - test-framework
- - test-framework-hunit
- - xcb-types
- Please add them, using `cabal gen-bounds` for suggestions. For more
information see: https://pvp.haskell.org/

Let's add some upper bounds, and introduce `cabal check` to CI so that
hopefully we can fix this stuff in the future.

commit.message:
add an automatic-github-releaser script

Per [1] it would be nice to have (Github) releases, since that e-mails
people who have subscribed to that setting. This will (hopefully, as-yet
untested) create them automagically when I push a new tag.

[1]: https://github.com/tych0/xcffib/commit/517169a2fb6dcc127059f581d3890e0861e2e950#comments

Signed-off-by: Tycho Andersen <tycho@tycho.pizza>

build against xcb-proto 1.16.0

We can finally get rid of the --builtins=CW hack (for certain versions...)!
I will probably do a release soon to capture this. But let's at least run
some CI against it for now.

Signed-off-by: Tycho Andersen <tycho@tycho.pizza>

Release v1.4.0

Warning: this has a minor API breakage for libraries importing xcffib's
ffi instance; we switched to the "in-line" ffi mode, so you'll have to do
something like:

-    from xcffib.ffi_build import ffi as xcb_ffi
+    from xcffib.ffi import ffi as xcb_ffi

if you were consuming xcffib's ffi export.

Signed-off-by: Tycho Andersen <tycho@tycho.pizza>

ffi instance; we switched to the "in-line" ffi mode, so you'll have to do
something like:

-    from xcffib.ffi_build import ffi as xcb_ffi
+    from xcffib.ffi import ffi as xcb_ffi

if you were consuming xcffib's ffi export.

Fix `List.to_string()`

Given this program as an example:

```python
import xcffib
import xcffib.randr
import xcffib.xproto

xconn = xcffib.Connection()
xrandr = xconn(xcffib.randr.key)
try:
	setup = xconn.get_setup()
	for screen in setup.roots:
		scrn_rsrcs = xrandr.GetScreenResources(screen.root).reply()
		for output in scrn_rsrcs.outputs:
			info = xrandr.GetOutputInfo(output, xcffib.XCB_CURRENT_TIME).reply()
			print(info.name.to_string())
finally:
	xconn.disconnect()
```

A `TypeError: 'int' object is not subscriptable` error is thrown.  With this patch it prints the name of each output as expected:

```
eDP-1
DP-1
DP-2
DP-3
DP-4
```

generator: handle paramrefs appropriately

paramref is really another hack for dynamically sized types (everywhere
else in the binding would declare these things as a list...).

We get:

    xcffib/xinput.py:288:54: F821 undefined name 'num_axes'

This object doesn't actually know the number of axes it has on the wire..
those come from a different request, and we're supposed to grab it from the
context in which the request was made.

Luckily, there is only one of these, so we can just hardcode the behavior
and explicitly error out if anyone ever adds another one.

Signed-off-by: Tycho Andersen <tycho@tycho.pizza>
